ana Davis</span></figcaption></div></figure></div><div class="f6782b90" data-testid="byline" data-scp="hidden"><div class="a1e09724"><div class="a1497183"><div class="b31aa83a ed1de826 f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><div class="f7f7e985"><a class="b12721a6" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/authors/ellen-airhart/" data-gtm-trigger="author_image_clicks" data-author-name="Ellen Airhart" data-scp="author_image"><div class="ec5f8867 global_chapter__arp_image"><img loading="lazy" alt="Ellen Airhart" itemProp="image" src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/ellen-airhart.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=60&amp;crop=1:1&amp;width=50" data-src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/ellen-airhart.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=60&amp;crop=1:1&amp;width=50" data-srcset="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/ellen-airhart.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=60&amp;crop=1:1&amp;width=50 320w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/ellen-airhart.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=60&amp;crop=1:1&amp;width=50&amp;dpr=1.5 480w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/ellen-airhart.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=60&amp;crop=1:1&amp;width=50&amp;dpr=2 640w" width="50" height="50" class="cf3feb4c c882c9ce"/></div></a></div><div class="cdb485da"><p class="a90f7598">By <a class="e31bedc8" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/authors/ellen-airhart/" data-gtm-trigger="author_name_clicks" data-author-name="Ellen Airhart" data-scp="author_name">Ellen Airhart</a></p><p class="c8779cf9" data-scp="author_byline">Ellen Airhart writes about emergency preparedness and sanitation. She&#x27;s used blood and dog excrement to test cleaning products.</p></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></header></div><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 a3bb01fc dfed01f2 f8687b84"><aside class="d4496375 c893684a" data-scp="hidden"><div id="review-note" class="b3ed220c" data-scp="note hidden" data-aside-note-component="note" data-aside-note-header="FYI" data-gtm-element="aside_note"><div class="e1d990bd a188437f "><span>FYI</span></div><div class="a397a4ae a6e487fe b8b93aa3" data-scp="note_body"><p>We’ve updated this guide with several new picks, including the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/54940/192466/4/167818/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/54940/192466/4/167818/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="sidenote" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="54940" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/54940/192466/4/167818/?merchant=Amazon" data-aside-note-component="note" data-aside-note-header="FYI">LifeStraw Max</a> water filter and <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/38478/162606/4/167856/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/38478/162606/4/167856/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="sidenote" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="38478" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/38478/162606/4/167856/?merchant=Amazon" data-aside-note-component="note" data-aside-note-header="FYI">Jackery Explorer 1000</a> portable power station, and added a section on accessibility considerations.</p></div><time class="bc361495 dbef455d" dateTime="2023-08" data-scp="note_date"><span>August 2023</span></time></div></aside></div><div class="b9c067b5 eb5163eb f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0 ba640706 a7fb3038"><section class="e60ecf56" data-gtm-element="lede"><p>Emergency-supply checklists are abundant across the internet, but many roundups can be intimidating in their breadth and their specificity. In reality, for the most part you can assemble a basic emergency kit for your home out of stuff you may already own. And there’s no such thing as a single kit that’s exactly right for everyone.</p></section><section class="fbf8e677" data-gtm-element="intro"><p>
“I think we focus too much on there trying to be one right way to prepare,” said Jonathan McNamara, a regional communications manager for the Red Cross. “You should definitely feel free to customize it for your family.”</p><p>That said, there are some essentials that everyone should have on hand in a dedicated bin if you need to shelter in place during a disaster. We understand the temptation to pick up a ready-made emergency kit—both the at-home and go-bag varieties—and call it a day. But building your own kit ensures quality control and allows you to customize it to fit your needs.</p><p>The items here are organized into six key categories that you can tackle one at a time to make sure you have your bases covered.</p><p>For more information on tools and preparedness for specific disaster scenarios, read our guides to <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/top-10-tools-to-help-you-ride-out-the-next-hurricane/">hurricane</a>, <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/tools-to-prepare-for-wildfire/">wildfire</a>, and <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-tools-for-earthquake-preparedness/">earthquake</a> preparedness. We also have a guide to building a <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-gear-for-your-bug-out-bag/">go bag</a>, should you need to evacuate your home.</p></section></div></div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"></div></div><div class="a1497183"><button type="button" class="eabd010d" aria-labelledby="btt_label"><svg viewBox="0 0 10 10" fill="currentColor" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="d1bc18f7"><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M9.44194 4.55806C9.68602 4.80213 9.68602 5.19786 9.44194 5.44194L5.46447 9.41942C5.22039 9.66349 4.82466 9.66349 4.58058 9.41942C4.33651 9.17534 4.33651 8.77961 4.58058 8.53553L7.49112 5.625L1 5.625C0.654823 5.625 0.375 5.34518 0.375 5C0.375001 4.65482 0.654822 4.375 1 4.375L7.49112 4.375L4.58058 1.46446C4.3365 1.22039 4.3365 0.824659 4.58058 0.580581C4.82466 0.336503 5.22039 0.336504 5.46447 0.580581L9.44194 4.55806Z"></path></svg><span id="btt_label">Back to top</span></button><div class="ab72109b f21e64f1 b5823c44 bdfcf243"><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><section id="table-of-contents" class="ffed1540" data-scp="removed" data-testid="toc" data-gtm-element="toc"><header class="d4645bc9"><h2 class="b6525d53">The research</h2></header><ul class="c7c94963"><li class="cb4e898e" data-testid="toc-chapter"><a href="#why-you-should-trust-us" data-gtm-element="review_toc_link" data-jumplink-index="1" data-gtm-trigger="jump_link" data-toc-name="Why you should trust us">Why you should trust us</a></li><li class="cb4e898e" data-testid="toc-chapter"><a href="#a-checklist-of-first-steps" data-gtm-element="review_toc_link" data-jumplink-index="2" data-gtm-trigger="jump_link" data-toc-name="A checklist of first steps">A checklist of first steps</a></li><li class="cb4e898e" data-testid="toc-chapter"><a href="#food-and-water" data-gtm-element="review_toc_link" data-jumplink-index="3" data-gtm-trigger="jump_link" data-toc-name="Food and water">Food and water</a></li><li class="cb4e898e" data-testid="toc-chapter"><a href="#health-and-hygiene" data-gtm-element="review_toc_link" data-jumplink-index="4" data-gtm-trigger="jump_link" data-toc-name="Health and hygiene">Health and hygiene</a></li><li class="cb4e898e" data-testid="toc-chapter"><a href="#light-and-heat" data-gtm-element="review_toc_link" data-jumplink-index="5" data-gtm-trigger="jump_link" data-toc-name="Light and heat">Light and heat</a></li><li class="cb4e898e" data-testid="toc-chapter"><a href="#communication-and-power" data-gtm-element="review_toc_link" data-jumplink-index="6" data-gtm-trigger="jump_link" data-toc-name="Communication and power">Communication and power</a></li><li class="cb4e898e" data-testid="toc-chapter"><a href="#tools" data-gtm-element="review_toc_link" data-jumplink-index="7" data-gtm-trigger="jump_link" data-toc-name="Tools">Tools</a></li><li class="cb4e898e" data-testid="toc-chapter"><a href="#storage" data-gtm-element="review_toc_link" data-jumplink-index="8" data-gtm-trigger="jump_link" data-toc-name="Storage">Storage</a></li><li class="cb4e898e" data-testid="toc-chapter"><a href="#accessibility-and-emergency-prep" data-gtm-element="review_toc_link" data-jumplink-index="9" data-gtm-trigger="jump_link" data-toc-name="Accessibility and emergency prep">Accessibility and emergency prep</a></li><li class="cb4e898e" data-testid="toc-chapter"><a href="#community-and-mental-health-care" data-gtm-element="review_toc_link" data-jumplink-index="10" data-gtm-trigger="jump_link" data-toc-name="Community and mental health care">Community and mental health care</a></li><li class="cb4e898e" data-testid="toc-chapter"><a href="#additional-emergency-prep-considerations" data-gtm-element="review_toc_link" data-jumplink-index="11" data-gtm-trigger="jump_link" data-toc-name="Additional emergency prep considerations">Additional emergency prep considerations</a></li><li class="cb4e898e" data-testid="toc-chapter"><a href="#disaster-specific-considerations" data-gtm-element="review_toc_link" data-jumplink-index="12" data-gtm-trigger="jump_link" data-toc-name="Disaster-specific considerations">Disaster-specific considerations</a></li><li class="cb4e898e" data-testid="toc-chapter"><a href="#sources" data-gtm-element="review_toc_link" data-jumplink-index="13" data-gtm-trigger="jump_link" data-toc-name="Sources">Sources</a></li></ul></section></div></div></div><section class="b6d81848 d47f7b03" id="why-you-should-trust-us" expanded=""><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0 e5f9b502"><h2 class="e823fba7" aria-controls="why-you-should-trust-us-panel" aria-selected="true" role="tab" tabindex="0" data-gtm-element="chapter_heading" data-gtm-trigger="single_chapter" data-chapter-name="Why you should trust us" data-expand-close="close" data-chapter-index="1">Why you should trust us</h2></div></div><div id="why-you-should-trust-us-panel" class="fa265be5" aria-labelledby="why-you-should-trust-us" aria-hidden="false" role="tabpanel"><div class=" chapter__content-wrapper"><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>Since 2017, this guide has been a collective effort among staff writers and editors who have trained for disaster preparedness, put their knowledge to use during natural disasters, and collectively logged hundreds of hours of research in this field to come up with a list of essentials that are indispensable in a natural disaster and helpful in everyday life, too.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>Staff writer Ellen Airhart has worked on our guides to <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/top-10-tools-to-help-you-ride-out-the-next-hurricane/">hurricane</a>, <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/tools-to-prepare-for-wildfire/">wildfire</a> and <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-tools-for-earthquake-preparedness/">earthquake preparedness</a>. For the most recent iteration of this guide, she spoke to eight new experts, including FEMA, Red Cross, and CDC representatives; an architect and an accessibility advocate.</p></div></div></div></div></div></section><section class="b6d81848 d47f7b03" id="a-checklist-of-first-steps" expanded=""><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0 e5f9b502"><h2 class="e823fba7" aria-controls="a-checklist-of-first-steps-panel" aria-selected="true" role="tab" tabindex="0" data-gtm-element="chapter_heading" data-gtm-trigger="single_chapter" data-chapter-name="A checklist of first steps" data-expand-close="close" data-chapter-index="2">A checklist of first steps</h2></div></div><div id="a-checklist-of-first-steps-panel" class="fa265be5" aria-labelledby="a-checklist-of-first-steps" aria-hidden="false" role="tabpanel"><div class=" chapter__content-wrapper"><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>Disaster prep is about much more than just buying stuff.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><ul><li>Develop a <a href="http://www.ready.gov/make-a-plan" rel="noopener" target="_blank">communication plan</a> with your family.</li><li>Take a <a href="http://www.redcross.org/ux/take-a-class" rel="noopener" target="_blank">first aid course</a>.</li><li>Find out whether a <a href="http://www.fema.gov/community-emergency-response-teams" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Community Emergency Response Team (CERT) class</a>, which will provide training for volunteer emergency efforts like light search-and-rescue operations, is happening in your area (you can usually attend at no cost).</li><li>Participate in community events, such as the <a href="http://www.shakeout.org/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">ShakeOut earthquake drills</a> held each October.</li><li>Mark your calendar to review and refresh your emergency kit once a year.</li></ul></div></div></div></div></div></section><section class="b6d81848 d47f7b03" id="food-and-water" expanded=""><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0 e5f9b502"><h2 class="e823fba7" aria-controls="food-and-water-panel" aria-selected="true" role="tab" tabindex="0" data-gtm-element="chapter_heading" data-gtm-trigger="single_chapter" data-chapter-name="Food and water" data-expand-close="close" data-chapter-index="3">Food and water</h2></div></div><div id="food-and-water-panel" class="fa265be5" aria-labelledby="food-and-water" aria-hidden="false" role="tabpanel"><div class=" chapter__content-wrapper"><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p><a href="https://www.fema.gov/pdf/library/f&amp;web.pdf" rel="noopener" target="_blank">FEMA (PDF)</a> recommends that you keep a three-day supply of water on hand—a gallon per person per day. But that’s for drinking and doesn’t cover basic hygiene needs.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>If you have the space for it, we think that stockpiling a 14-day supply of a gallon per person is a reasonable goal, especially if you live in an earthquake zone. We found two options for ensuring an adequate water supply: <a href="#water_storage">dedicated containers</a> or a water purification system.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><h3>Water purification</h3></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 bdfcf243"><figure id="attachment_333003" class="wp-caption alignnone"><div class="ec5f8867 global_chapter__arp_image b71ff2c5"><img loading="lazy" alt="The LifeStraw Max, our pick for the best water purifier." src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/08/emergencypreparedness-2048px-08267-3x2-1.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=320" data-src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/08/emergencypreparedness-2048px-08267-3x2-1.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=1024" data-srcset="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/08/emergencypreparedness-2048px-08267-3x2-1.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=1024 1024w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/08/emergencypreparedness-2048px-08267-3x2-1.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=1024&amp;dpr=1.5 1536w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/08/emergencypreparedness-2048px-08267-3x2-1.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=1024&amp;dpr=2 2048w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/08/emergencypreparedness-2048px-08267-3x2-1.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=980 980w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/08/emergencypreparedness-2048px-08267-3x2-1.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=980&amp;dpr=1.5 1470w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/08/emergencypreparedness-2048px-08267-3x2-1.jpg?aut