ods, hurricanes, and <a href="https://www.acs.org/pressroom/presspacs/2022/acs-presspac-june-8-2022/link-between-wildfires-and-drinking-water-contamination.html" rel="noopener" target="_blank">wildfires</a> can contaminate local water, rendering it unsafe to drink without boiling it or chemically treating it first. The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/54940/192466/4/167818/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/54940/192466/4/167818/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_food-and-water" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="54940" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/54940/192466/4/167818/?merchant=Amazon">LifeStraw Max</a> is a device that cleans water easily by filtering virtually all viruses, bacteria, and other pathogens from contaminated water, in addition to reducing sediment and many industrial and agricultural chemicals and dissolved metals.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>You don’t need electricity to use it, and it’s a viable long-term option during a boil-water advisory. It can purify up to 40 gallons per hour, and its filters can cleanse 26,500 gallons before you need to replace them. We know its price tag can be prohibitively expensive, but if a group of neighbors shares the purchase cost it can provide clean water to multiple households for weeks.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><h3 id="water_storage">Water storage</h3></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><div class="ebb615ab global-cob eaaa9459 e1e566ad d097cc30" data-scp="callout"><h4 class="d02b79e1 e20b6350" data-scp="callout_label">Our pick</h4><div id="callout-chapter-1-2" class="fd1ac384" data-scp="callout_item" data-testid="callout" data-pid="11016"><span class="ddf294c5"><div class="fabe3ad3"><div class="e14704b2" role="button" tabindex="0" data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="11016"><span aria-label="Save Product" class="a478f5d2  " data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="11016"></span></div></div></span><div class="f1cabe17"><div class="f31f6df1"><div class="efc734d0 eae76d54"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11016/178454/4/167754?merchant=REI" class="fa8c1483 product-merchant-link-button" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-store="REI" data-vars-store="REI" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11016/178454/4/167754?merchant=REI" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_image" data-scp="removed" tabindex="-1" data-pid="11016" data-gtm-context="inline"><div class="ec5f8867 global_chapter__arp_image"><img alt="" itemProp="image" data-src="https://d1b5h9psu9yexj.cloudfront.net/11016/Reliance-Aqua-Tainer_20180221-165026_full.jpg" width="570" height="380" class="cf3feb4c c882c9ce" loading="lazy"/></div></a></div><div class="ce2bb787"><div><h3 class="b550f131 e26624a1 a1a87f29"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11016/178454/4/167754?merchant=REI" class="dfb6b88d" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" title="Reliance Aqua-Tainer 7-Gallon" data-gtm-element="callout_product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="REI" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="11016" data-store="REI" data-vars-store="REI" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11016/178454/4/167754?merchant=REI" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_name" data-scp="callout_product" data-gtm-context="inline">Reliance Aqua-Tainer 7-Gallon</a></h3><h2 class="eafb159a"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11016/178454/4/167754?merchant=REI" class="c44f6873" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" title="The best water storage container" data-store="REI" data-vars-store="REI" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11016/178454/4/167754?merchant=REI" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_title" data-scp="callout_title" data-pid="11016" data-gtm-context="inline">The best water storage container</a></h2></div><p class="ec57f3ca" data-scp="callout_description">This sturdy, portable 7-gallon plastic jug has smart features, including a tethered air vent for easy pouring.</p><div class="dded66b7"><div data-scp="removed"><h4 class="efa3259d">Buying Options</h4><div class="b279b202 product-pricebox-0" data-source-id-order="0" data-country-code="US"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11016/178454/4/167754?merchant=REI" class="b50e01ee" data-gtm-element="callout_buy_button_impression" data-link-type="button" data-merchant="REI" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="11016" data-store="REI" data-vars-store="REI" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11016/178454/4/167754?merchant=REI" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-gtm-context="inline" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_button">Buy<!-- --> from <span>REI</span></a><p class="ab4df9c8">May be out of stock</p></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>Rigid water containers made of blue polyethylene consistently perform better than opaque collapsible ones for both pouring and storage. They’re also more durable and leak resistant. We called in five models for testing before concluding that the oversize, rugged, 7-gallon <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11016/178454/4/167819/?merchant=REI" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="REI" data-pick-type-id="1" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11016/178454/4/167819/?merchant=REI" data-vars-store="REI" data-gtm-context="chapter_food-and-water" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="REI" data-pid="11016" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11016/178454/4/167819/?merchant=REI">Reliance Aqua-Tainer</a> is the best overall choice for disaster-preparedness purposes.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The Aqua-Tainer has a built-in, break-proof handle that is relatively comfortable to use. The spigot is stored inside the cap when not in use, reducing the risk of its cracking or smashing. This jug also has a tethered, screw-on air-vent valve, so there are no tiny parts to lose, and there’s no risk of leakage.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>A couple of caveats: Unlike some other Reliance models, the Aqua-Tainer is not designed to be stacked. When full, the 7-gallon jug weighs close to 60 pounds. So the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11018/30950/4/168451/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11018/30950/4/168451/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_food-and-water" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="11018" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11018/30950/4/168451/?merchant=Amazon">Reliance Aqua-Pak 5-Gallon</a>, which usually sells for more, may be a better choice for people who require a lighter lift. Or you could just buy the bigger, cheaper jug and avoid filling it to the brim.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>Reliance officially advises that people replace emergency water stored in its containers every 90 days. To avoid contaminating water with bacteria, clean the container first, and wash your hands vigorously before filling it.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>If you’re concerned about contamination after opening the jug and don’t own a <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/54940/192466/4/167818/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/54940/192466/4/167818/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_food-and-water" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="54940" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/54940/192466/4/167818/?merchant=Amazon">LifeStraw Max</a>, boiling water is the safest way to treat it. But be sure to let water boil for a full minute—three, if you’re at an altitude higher than 5,000 feet. And keep in mind that some water will evaporate, which is a concern if your supply is low.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><div class="ebb615ab global-cob eaaa9459 e1e566ad d097cc30" data-scp="callout"><h4 class="d02b79e1 e20b6350" data-scp="callout_label">Our pick</h4><div id="callout-chapter-1-3" class="fd1ac384" data-scp="callout_item" data-testid="callout" data-pid="29126"><span class="ddf294c5"><div class="fabe3ad3"><div class="e14704b2" role="button" tabindex="0" data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="29126"><span aria-label="Save Product" class="a478f5d2  " data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="29126"></span></div></div></span><div class="f1cabe17"><div class="f31f6df1"><div class="efc734d0 eae76d54"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/29126/164124/4/167755?merchant=Amazon" class="fa8c1483 product-merchant-link-button" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/29126/164124/4/167755?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_image" data-scp="removed" tabindex="-1" data-pid="29126" data-gtm-context="inline"><div class="ec5f8867 global_chapter__arp_image"><img alt="" itemProp="image" data-src="https://d1b5h9psu9yexj.cloudfront.net/29126/Augason-Farms-55-Gallon-Water-Storage-Barrel_20181022-155548_full.jpeg" width="570" height="380" class="cf3feb4c c882c9ce" loading="lazy"/></div></a></div><div class="ce2bb787"><div><h3 class="b550f131 e26624a1 a1a87f29"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/29126/164124/4/167755?merchant=Amazon" class="dfb6b88d" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" title="Augason Farms 55-Gallon Water Storage Barrel" data-gtm-element="callout_product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="29126" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/29126/164124/4/167755?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_name" data-scp="callout_product" data-gtm-context="inline">Augason Farms 55-Gallon Water Storage Barrel</a></h3><h2 class="eafb159a"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/29126/164124/4/167755?merchant=Amazon" class="c44f6873" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" title="The best water storage container for more than two people" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/29126/164124/4/167755?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_title" data-scp="callout_title" data-pid="29126" data-gtm-context="inline">The best water storage container for more than two people</a></h2></div><p class="ec57f3ca" data-scp="callout_description">This large drum, which is made of food-grade plastic, allows you to store an entire family’s supply of water.</p><div class="dded66b7"><div data-scp="removed"><h4 class="efa3259d">Buying Options</h4><div class="b279b202 product-pricebox-0" data-source-id-order="0" data-country-code="US"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/29126/164124/4/167755?merchant=Amazon" class="b50e01ee" data-gtm-element="callout_buy_button_impression" data-link-type="button" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="29126" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/29126/164124/4/167755?merchant=Amazon" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-gtm-context="inline" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_button"><span>$119</span> from <span>Amazon</span></a></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>A family of four would need eight Aqua-Tainers to store a minimum two-week supply of water. An alternative option is to purchase a 55-gallon drum. We like this one from <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/29126/164124/4/167820/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/29126/164124/4/167820/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_food-and-water" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="29126" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/29126/164124/4/167820/?merchant=Amazon">Augason Farms</a>, (but, honestly, we’ve found most blue 55-gallon drums of this type to be essentially the same).</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>You’ll need <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/57406/193420/4/167821/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/57406/193420/4/167821/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_food-and-water" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="57406" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/57406/193420/4/167821/?merchant=Amazon">a pump</a> to get the water out, and if you’re concerned about contamination, you can treat it with <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/25372/148787/4/167823/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/25372/148787/4/167823/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_food-and-water" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="25372" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/25372/148787/4/167823/?merchant=Amazon">chlorine dioxide</a> tablets. For simplicity’s sake, we still recommend boiling water.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The CDC recommends swapping out stored water <a href="https://www.cdc.gov/healthywater/emergency/creating-storing-emergency-water-supply.html" rel="noopener" target="_blank">every six months</a>, and ideally you should keep your water in a cool, shaded location. If it’s on concrete that gets hot, place it on a wood platform before filling. These drums will weigh 480 pounds when full, so if you’re in an earthquake zone, don’t place them where they might potentially tumble off a ledge or down a hillside and hurt someone.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><h3>Food</h3></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The best emergency-food strategy is to stock your cupboards full of the shelf-stable canned and dry goods you love and routinely eat—think soups, fruits, vegetables, beans, grains, cereals, pastas, nuts, dried fruit, peanut butter, and boxed milk (which, before it’s opened, doesn’t need refrigeration). These items are less likely to expire, since you’re eating and replacing them regularly.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>FEMA has a <a href="https://www.fema.gov/pdf/library/f&amp;web.pdf" rel="noopener" target="_blank">list (PDF)</a> of some pantry staples that may be stored indefinitely and Popular Mechanics <a href="https://www.popularmechanics.com/adventure/tips/g1812/how-to-stock-your-disaster-pantry/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">has a plan</a> we like that you can follow. You’ll also need a good can opener; we <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-can-opener/">recommend</a> the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11828/33129/4/167875/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11828/33129/4/167875/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_food-and-water" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="11828" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11828/33129/4/167875/?merchant=Amazon">EZ-Duz-It.</a></p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>If you have time before an impending emergency—for example, if you suspect you might lose power during a hurricane—set your refrigerator and freezer to the lowest possible setting. This will keep food <a href="https://www.canr.msu.edu/news/keep_cold_food_safe_during_a_power_outage#:~:text=Pre%2Dplanning&amp;text=Refrigerators%20should%20always%20be%20kept,the%20refrigerator%20and%20the%20freezer." rel="noopener" target="_blank">edible for longer</a> if you lose electricity. If you keep the freezer door closed, that food should stay safe to eat for 72 hours into a blackout.</p></div></div></div></div></div></section><section class="b6d81848 d47f7b03" id="health-and-hygiene" expanded=""><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0 e5f9b502"><h2 class="e823fba7" aria-controls="health-and-hygiene-panel" aria-selected="true" role="tab" tabindex="0" data-gtm-element="chapter_heading" data-gtm-trigger="single_chapter" data-chapter-name="Health and hygiene" data-expand-close="close" data-chapter-index="4">Health and hygiene</h2></div></div><div id="health-and-hygiene-panel" class="fa265be5" aria-labelledby="health-and-hygiene" aria-hidden="false" role="tabpanel"><div class=" chapter__content-wrapper"><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The consequences of not having access to clean water are far greater than mere stink. Staying clean helps you avoid spreading germs or harboring infection—common problems during extended disasters. (Gastrointestinal illness and wound infections were some of the most common infectious diseases that occurred in the aftermath of <a href="https://www.cidrap.umn.edu/campylobacter/hurricane-katrina-sparks-fears-disease-outbreaks" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Hurricane Katrina</a>, with at least five people dying from otherwise-minor wounds or abrasions.)</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>A quality first aid kit, hand sanitizer, face masks, and superthick garbage bags are emergency-kit must-haves, in our opinion. Many people also store extras of basic personal-hygiene items (toothbrush and toothpaste, soap, tampons or menstrual pads, diapers), and a spare pair of glasses.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The Red Cross advocates stashing <a href="https://www.redcross.org/about-us/news-and-events/press-release/2020/national-preparedness-month-red-cross-research-shows-older-adults-more-vulnerable-in-disasters.html" rel="noopener" target="_blank">a month’s worth</a> of any prescription medications you take since supply chains could be interrupted and pharmacies could be closed after a disaster. But this could be difficult to obtain ahead of time, and our best advice is to have a discussion with your doctor.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><h3>First aid kit</h3></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 bdfcf243"><figure id="attachment_332999" class="wp-caption alignnone"><div class="ec5f8867 global_chapter__arp_image b71ff2c5"><img loading="lazy" alt="The First Aid Only 298 Piece All-Purpose First Aid Kit." src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/08/emergencypreparedness-2048px-2806.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=320" data-src="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/08/emergencypreparedness-2048px-2806.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=1024" data-srcset="https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/08/emergencypreparedness-2048px-2806.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=1024 1024w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/08/emergencypreparedness-2048px-2806.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=1024&amp;dpr=1.5 1536w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/08/emergencypreparedness-2048px-2806.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=1024&amp;dpr=2 2048w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/08/emergencypreparedness-2048px-2806.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=980 980w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/08/emergencypreparedness-2048px-2806.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=980&amp;dpr=1.5 1470w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/08/emergencypreparedness-2048px-2806.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=980&amp;dpr=2 1960w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/08/emergencypreparedness-2048px-2806.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=768 768w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/08/emergencypreparedness-2048px-2806.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=768&amp;dpr=1.5 1152w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/08/emergencypreparedness-2048px-2806.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=768&amp;dpr=2 1536w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/08/emergencypreparedness-2048px-2806.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=480 480w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/08/emergencypreparedness-2048px-2806.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=480&amp;dpr=1.5 720w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/08/emergencypreparedness-2048px-2806.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=480&amp;dpr=2 960w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/08/emergencypreparedness-2048px-2806.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=320 320w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/08/emergencypreparedness-2048px-2806.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=320&amp;dpr=1.5 480w,https://cdn.thewirecutter.com/wp-content/media/2023/08/emergencypreparedness-2048px-2806.jpg?auto=webp&amp;quality=75&amp;width=320&amp;dpr=2 640w" width="2048" height="1365" class="cf3feb4c c882c9ce alignnone size-full wp-image-332999"/></div><figcaption class="wp-caption-text"> <!-- --> <span class="wp-caption-text wp-caption-credit">Photo: Sarah Kobos</span></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><div class="ebb615ab global-cob eaaa9459 e1e566ad d097cc30" data-scp="callout"><h4 class="d02b79e1 e20b6350" data-scp="callout_label">Our pick</h4><div id="callout-chapter-1-4" class="fd1ac384" data-scp="callout_item" data-testid="callout" data-pid="21448"><span class="ddf294c5"><div class="fabe3ad3"><div class="e14704b2" role="button" tabindex="0" data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="21448"><span aria-label="Save Product" class="a478f5d2  " data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="21448"></span></div></div></span><div class="f1cabe17"><div class="f31f6df1"><div class="efc734d0 eae76d54"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/21448/117266/4/167760?merchant=Amazon" class="fa8c1483 product-merchant-link-button" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/21448/117266/4/167760?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_image" data-scp="removed" tabindex="-1" data-pid="21448" data-gtm-context="inline"><div class="ec5f8867 global_chapter__arp_image"><img alt="" itemProp="image" data-src="https://d1b5h9psu9yexj.cloudfront.net/21448/First-Aid-Only-First-Aid-Essentials-Kit_20181018-161204_full.jpeg" width="570" height="380" class="cf3feb4c c882c9ce" loading="lazy"/></div></a></div><div class="ce2bb787"><div><h3 class="b550f131 e26624a1 a1a87f29"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/21448/117266/4/167760?merchant=Amazon" class="dfb6b88d" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" title="First Aid Only 298 Piece All-Purpose First Aid Kit (FAO-442)" data-gtm-element="callout_product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="21448" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/21448/117266/4/167760?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_name" data-scp="callout_product" data-gtm-context="inline">First Aid Only 298 Piece All-Purpose First Aid Kit (FAO-442)</a></h3><h2 class="eafb159a"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/21448/117266/4/167760?merchant=Amazon" class="c44f6873" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" title="The best general-use first aid kit" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/21448/117266/4/167760?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_title" data-scp="callout_title" data-pid="21448" data-gtm-context="inline">The best general-use first aid kit</a></h2></div><p class="ec57f3ca" data-scp="callout_description">This First Aid Only kit has all the necessary gear for treating minor scrapes, cuts, and burns (including an abundance of adhesive bandages), and it includes a decent first aid booklet.</p><div class="dded66b7"><div data-scp="removed"><h4 class="efa3259d">Buying Options</h4><div class="b279b202 product-pricebox-0" data-source-id-order="0" data-country-code="US"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/21448/117266/4/167760?merchant=Amazon" class="b50e01ee" data-gtm-element="callout_buy_button_impression" data-link-type="button" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="21448" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/21448/117266/4/167760?merchant=Amazon" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-gtm-context="inline" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_button"><span>$18</span> from <span>Amazon</span></a></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>Everyone should take a <a href="http://www.redcross.org/ux/take-a-class" rel="noopener" target="_blank">basic first aid course</a>. Once you have those skills, you’ll need some supplies. The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/21448/117266/4/167827/?merch