ion">A flashlight is essential in an emergency, and this ThruNite model has a wide range of brightness settings and an easy-to-use interface.</p><div class="dded66b7"><div data-scp="removed"><h4 class="efa3259d">Buying Options</h4><div class="b279b202 product-pricebox-0" data-source-id-order="0" data-country-code="US"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/18258/165376/4/167768?merchant=Amazon" class="b50e01ee" data-gtm-element="callout_buy_button_impression" data-link-type="button" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="18258" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/18258/165376/4/167768?merchant=Amazon" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-gtm-context="inline" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_button"><span>$25</span> from <span>Amazon</span></a></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>Since there’s no way to know how long you might be without power, you need a long-lasting LED flashlight. <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-flashlight/">We love</a> the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/18258/165376/4/167843/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/18258/165376/4/167843/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_light-and-heat" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="18258" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/18258/165376/4/167843/?merchant=Amazon">ThruNite Archer 2A V3</a>. On the highest of its four brightness settings, we were able to see trees 500 feet away. It has a strobe setting for emergency signaling and boasts a number of other features found on more-expensive lights: It doesn’t roll on a flat surface, it stands upright on its rear end, it can survive a 1-meter drop or full immersion in water.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>This flashlight also has a long battery life. According to the manufacturer, when the flashlight is on its highest setting, it will run for 96 minutes, but on its lowest setting, it can run for roughly 28 days (on the medium setting it runs for 11 hours, and on the low setting it lasts for four days). Wirecutter’s Doug Mahoney even hung it in the bathroom overnight as a night light for his kids during a blackout that lasted several days. It runs on two <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/10469/193492/4/167844/?merchant=Walmart" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Walmart" data-pick-type-id="1" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/10469/193492/4/167844/?merchant=Walmart" data-vars-store="Walmart" data-gtm-context="chapter_light-and-heat" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Walmart" data-pid="10469" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/10469/193492/4/167844/?merchant=Walmart">AA batteries</a>, so make sure to have <a href="#disposable_batteries">extras on hand</a>.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><h3>Headlamp</h3></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><div class="ebb615ab global-cob eaaa9459 e1e566ad d097cc30" data-scp="callout"><h4 class="d02b79e1 e20b6350" data-scp="callout_label">Our pick</h4><div id="callout-chapter-1-12" class="fd1ac384" data-scp="callout_item" data-testid="callout" data-pid="50537"><span class="ddf294c5"><div class="fabe3ad3"><div class="e14704b2" role="button" tabindex="0" data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-