art one. A lighter or matches are the easiest option, but you should have a backup plan in case you run out. A single magnesium fire starter can last for years. And using the better ones, a complete novice can successfully light a fire after just a few tries.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>We tested five top-rated models and found that <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11033/191752/4/167846/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11033/191752/4/167846/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_light-and-heat" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="11033" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11033/191752/4/167846/?merchant=Amazon">The Friendly Swede’s Easy-Grip Fire Starter</a> (two-pack) is the best choice. The trick to getting strong sparks with these tools is to scrape down the flint quickly and firmly, and this was easier to do with the Friendly Swede model’s relatively long flint than it was with smaller, cheaper tools.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>If you’d prefer to rely on an object that feels more familiar, the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11037/165832/4/167847/?merchant=REI" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="REI" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11037/165832/4/167847/?merchant=REI" data-vars-store="REI" data-gtm-context="chapter_light-and-heat" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="REI" data-pid="11037" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11037/165832/4/167847/?merchant=REI">UCO Stormproof Match Kit with Waterproof Case</a> worked well in our testing. These UCO matches will also stay lit in windy conditions and continue burning even when doused with water, thanks to the extra fuel that extends halfway down the length of the stick.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><h3>Fire starters</h3></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><div class="ebb615ab global-cob eaaa9459 e1e566ad d097cc30" data-scp="callout"><h4 class="d02b79e1 e20b6350" data-scp="callout_label">Our pick</h4><div id="callout-chapter-1-14" class="fd1ac384" data-scp="callout_item" data-testid="callout" data-pid="19111"><span class="ddf294c5"><div class="fabe3ad3"><div class="e14704b2" role="button" tabindex="0" data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="19111"><span aria-label="Save Product" class="a478f5d2  " data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="19111"></span></div></div></span><div class="f1cabe17"><div class="f31f6df1"><div class="efc734d0 eae76d54"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/19111/98606/4/167771?merchant=Amazon" class="fa8c1483 product-merchant-link-button" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/19111/98606/4/167771?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_image" data-scp="removed" tabindex="-1" data-pid="19111" data-gtm-context="inline"><div class="ec5f8867 global_chapter__arp_image"><img alt="" itemProp="image" data-src="https://d1b5h9psu9yexj.cloudfront.net/19111/Instafire-Fire-Starter_20200504-180344_full.jpg" width="570" height="380" class="cf3feb4c c882c9ce" loading="lazy"/></div></a></div><div class="ce2bb787"><div><h3 class="b550f131 e26624a1 a1a87f29"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/19111/98606/4/167771?merchant=Amazon" class="dfb6b88d" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" title="Instafire Fire Starter" data-gtm-element="callout_product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="19111" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/19111/98606/4/167771?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_name" data-scp="callout_product" data-gtm-context="inline">Instafire Fire Starter</a></h3><h2 class="eafb159a"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/19111/98606/4/167771?merchant=Amazon" class="c44f6873" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" title="The best fire starter" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/19111/98606/4/167771?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_title" data-scp="callout_title" data-pid="19111" data-gtm-context="inline">The best fire starter</a></h2></div><p class="ec57f3ca" data-scp="callout_description">Instafire burns hot and long, and a single packet can start multiple fires.</p><div class="dded66b7"><div data-scp="removed"><h4 class="efa3259d">Buying Options</h4><div class="b279b202 product-pricebox-0" data-source-id-order="0" data-country-code="US"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/19111/98606/4/167771?merchant=Amazon" class="b50e01ee" data-gtm-element="callout_buy_button_impression" data-link-type="button" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="19111" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/19111/98606/4/167771?merchant=Amazon" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-gtm-context="inline" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_button"><span>$32</span> from <span>Amazon</span><br/><span>(pack of 30)</span></a></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>You definitely don’t need a fire starter to light a fire, but if you’re dealing with wet wood or extreme conditions, it sure can make the process a lot easier. We found that <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/19111/98606/4/167849/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/19111/98606/4/167849/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_light-and-heat" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="19111" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/19111/98606/4/167849/?merchant=Amazon">Instafire’s Fire Starter</a> pouches are the best tool for quickly getting flames going. <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/9297/26567/4/167850/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/9297/26567/4/167850/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_light-and-heat" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="9297" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/9297/26567/4/167850/?merchant=Amazon">Weber’s Lighter Cubes</a> are another good option. They’re great for getting charcoal going in a grill (their original purpose), and they burn hot and long.</p></div></div></div></div></div></section><section class="b6d81848 d47f7b03" id="communication-and-power" expanded=""><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0 e5f9b502"><h2 class="e823fba7" aria-controls="communication-and-power-panel" aria-selected="true" role="tab" tabindex="0" data-gtm-element="chapter_heading" data-gtm-trigger="single_chapter" data-chapter-name="Communication and power" data-expand-close="close" data-chapter-index="6">Communication and power</h2></div></div><div id="communication-and-power-panel" class="fa265be5" aria-labelledby="communication-and-power" aria-hidden="false" role="tabpanel"><div class=" chapter__content-wrapper"><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>In an emergency, keeping yourself warm or cool in extreme temperatures, hearing the latest news and getting in touch with family and friends is paramount, but doing so can be tough when the electricity goes down. By investing in a few pieces of hardware, you’ll be able to power electronics until the local utility companies restore services to your neighborhood.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><h3>Portable generator</h3></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><div class="ebb615ab global-cob eaaa9459 e1e566ad d097cc30" data-scp="callout"><h4 class="d02b79e1 e20b6350" data-scp="callout_label">Our pick</h4><div id="callout-chapter-1-15" class="fd1ac384" data-scp="callout_item" data-testid="callout" data-pid="39922"><span class="ddf294c5"><div class="fabe3ad3"><div class="e14704b2" role="button" tabindex="0" data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="39922"><span aria-label="Save Product" class="a478f5d2  " data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="39922"></span></div></div></span><div class="f1cabe17"><div class="f31f6df1"><div class="efc734d0 eae76d54"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/39922/193503/4/167786?merchant=Amazon" class="fa8c1483 product-merchant-link-button" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/39922/193503/4/167786?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_image" data-scp="removed" tabindex="-1" data-pid="39922" data-gtm-context="inline"><div class="ec5f8867 global_chapter__arp_image"><img alt="" itemProp="image" data-src="https://d1b5h9psu9yexj.cloudfront.net/39922/Honda-EU2200i_20200728-202356_full.jpeg" width="570" height="380" class="cf3feb4c c882c9ce" loading="lazy"/></div></a></div><div class="ce2bb787"><div><h3 class="b550f131 e26624a1 a1a87f29"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/39922/193503/4/167786?merchant=Amazon" class="dfb6b88d" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" title="Honda EU2200i" data-gtm-element="callout_product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="39922" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/39922/193503/4/167786?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_name" data-scp="callout_product" data-gtm-context="inline">Honda EU2200i</a></h3><h2 class="eafb159a"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/39922/193503/4/167786?merchant=Amazon" class="c44f6873" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" title="The best generator" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/39922/193503/4/167786?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_title" data-scp="callout_title" data-pid="39922" data-gtm-context="inline">The best generator</a></h2></div><p class="ec57f3ca" data-scp="callout_description">The quietest, lightest, and most powerful 2,200-watt generator we tested is easy to start, and the Bluetooth app makes monitoring its power input simple.</p><div class="dded66b7"><div data-scp="removed"><h4 class="efa3259d">Buying Options</h4><div class="b279b202 product-pricebox-0" data-source-id-order="0" data-country-code="US"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/39922/193503/4/167786?merchant=Amazon" class="b50e01ee" data-gtm-element="callout_buy_button_impression" data-link-type="button" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="39922" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/39922/193503/4/167786?merchant=Amazon" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-gtm-context="inline" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_button"><span>$1,091</span> from <span>Amazon</span></a></div><div class="b279b202 product-pricebox-1" data-source-id-order="1" data-country-code="US"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/39922/164179/4/167786?merchant=Home%20Depot" class="b50e01ee" data-gtm-element="callout_buy_button_impression" data-link-type="button" data-merchant="Home Depot" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="39922" data-store="Home Depot" data-vars-store="Home Depot" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/39922/164179/4/167786?merchant=Home%20Depot" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-gtm-context="inline" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_button"><span>$1,399</span> from <span>Home Depot</span></a></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>We tested four 2,200-watt generators for our guide to <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-portable-generator/">portable generators</a>, and the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/39922/193503/4/167851/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/39922/193503/4/167851/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_communication-and-power" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="39922" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/39922/193503/4/167851/?merchant=Amazon">Honda EU2200i</a> is the best. It’s not big enough to power an entire house, but with some smart power management, you can use it to keep essentials like a space heater going during an emergency. The Honda was the quietest, lightest, and most powerful generator we looked at—it even <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-portable-generator/#our-pick-honda-eu2200i">exceeded its listed capabilities</a> and powered household items that caused the other generators to overload.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The EU2200i started on the first pull of the cord every single time we used it. You can easily monitor the Honda’s power output through a Bluetooth-connected app, so during an outage you can manage (and maximize) the generator’s operation from indoors.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The EU2200i also has an onboard carbon monoxide detector that shuts the generator down if a concentration of the deadly gas gets too high, which can happen if the generator is running in an enclosed area. <a href="https://www.npr.org/2019/12/04/784279242/carbon-monoxide-poisoning-from-portable-generators-proves-predictable-and-deadly" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Never run one</a> of these indoors or even in your garage with the doors open. For usage with appliances or tools indoors, you need to run an <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-extension-cords-for-your-home-and-garage/">extension cord</a>—likely through an open window.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>Honda generators have an excellent reputation and recognition in the industry as the gold standard, but this quality makes it expensive. The EU2200i is typically priced over $1,000, about $400 more than other gas options, but we think its ease of use and dependability are worth the extra cost.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><h3>Portable power station</h3></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><div class="ebb615ab global-cob eaaa9459 e1e566ad d097cc30" data-scp="callout"><h4 class="d02b79e1 e20b6350" data-scp="callout_label">Our pick</h4><div id="callout-chapter-1-16" class="fd1ac384" data-scp="callout_item" data-testid="callout" data-pid="38478"><span class="ddf294c5"><div class="fabe3ad3"><div class="e14704b2" role="button" tabindex="0" data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="38478"><span aria-label="Save Product" class="a478f5d2  " data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="38478"></span></div></div></span><div class="f1cabe17"><div class="f31f6df1"><div class="efc734d0 eae76d54"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/38478/162606/4/167788?merchant=Amazon" class="fa8c1483 product-merchant-link-button" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/38478/162606/4/167788?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_image" data-scp="removed" tabindex="-1" data-pid="38478" data-gtm-context="inline"><div class="ec5f8867 global_chapter__arp_image"><img alt="" itemProp="image" data-src="https://d1b5h9psu9yexj.cloudfront.net/38478/Jackery-Explorer-1000_20210810-211102_full.jpg" width="570" height="380" class="cf3feb4c c882c9ce" loading="lazy"/></div></a></div><div class="ce2bb787"><div><h3 class="b550f131 e26624a1 a1a87f29"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/38478/162606/4/167788?merchant=Amazon" class="dfb6b88d" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" title="Jackery Explorer 1000" data-gtm-element="callout_product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="38478" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/38478/162606/4/167788?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_name" data-scp="callout_product" data-gtm-context="inline">Jackery Explorer 1000</a></h3><h2 class="eafb159a"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/38478/162606/4/167788?merchant=Amazon" class="c44f6873" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" title="An alternative to a gas generator" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/38478/162606/4/167788?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_title" data-scp="callout_title" data-pid="38478" data-gtm-context="inline">An alternative to a gas generator</a></h2></div><p class="ec57f3ca" data-scp="callout_description">This giant battery offers a maximum output of 1,370 W in a portable and easy-to-use package. You can safely use it indoors because it doesn’t emit exhaust, but it’s not as powerful or long-lasting as a gas generator.</p><div class="dded66b7"><div data-scp="removed"><h4 class="efa3259d">Buying Options</h4><div class="b279b202 product-pricebox-0" data-source-id-order="0" data-country-code="US"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/38478/162606/4/167788?merchant=Amazon" class="b50e01ee" data-gtm-element="callout_buy_button_impression" data-link-type="button" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="38478" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/38478/162606/4/167788?merchant=Amazon" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-gtm-context="inline" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_button"><span>$999</span> from <span>Amazon</span></a></div><div class="b279b202 product-pricebox-1" data-source-id-order="1" data-country-code="US"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/38478/161914/4/167788?merchant=Jackery" class="b50e01ee" data-gtm-element="callout_buy_button_impression" data-link-type="button" data-merchant="Jackery" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="38478" data-store="Jackery" data-vars-store="Jackery" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/38478/161914/4/167788?merchant=Jackery" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-gtm-context="inline" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_button"><span>$999</span> from <span>Jackery</span></a></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>A <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-portable-power-stations/">portable power station</a> like the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/38478/162606/4/167852/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/38478/162606/4/167852/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_communication-and-power" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="38478" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/38478/162606/4/167852/?merchant=Amazon">Jackery Explorer 1000</a> is a great option if you want to use your power source indoors—where the fumes of a gas generator are dangerous—and you need more power than a <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-usb-battery-packs/">USB battery pack</a> can provide. The Jackery Explorer 1000 is light enough for the average adult to <a href="https://ohsonline.com/Articles/2018/02/01/Keep-Lifts-Between-the-Knees-and-Shoulders.aspx?m=1&amp;Page=1" rel="noopener" target="_blank">lift and carry safely</a>, yet it managed to run even the most power-hungry appliances in our tests, so it’s suitable for keeping most devices, such as a laptop, a CPAP machine, or even a small refrigerator running all day (or all night) long.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>Its easy-to-read screen shows input/output wattage and how much power remains in reserve. Plus, it has more output ports—three AC, two USB-A, and two USB-C—than almost any other portable power station we’ve tested.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><h3>Emergency weather radio</h3></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><div class="ebb615ab global-cob eaaa9459 e1e566ad d097cc30" data-scp="callout"><h4 class="d02b79e1 e20b6350" data-scp="callout_label">Our pick</h4><div id="callout-chapter-1-17" class="fd1ac384" data-scp="callout_item" data-testid="callout" data-pid="12995"><span class="ddf294c5"><div class="fabe3ad3"><div class="e14704b2" role="button" tabindex="0" data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="12995"><span aria-label="Save Product" class="a478f5d2  " data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="12995"></span></div></div></span><div class="f1cabe17"><div class="f31f6df1"><div class="efc734d0 eae76d54"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/12995/37027/4/167789?merchant=Amazon" class="fa8c1483 product-merchant-link-button" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/12995/37027/4/167789?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_image" data-scp="removed" tabindex="-1" data-pid="12995" data-gtm-context="inline"><div class="ec5f8867 global_chapter__arp_image"><img alt="" itemProp="image" data-src="https://d1b5h9psu9yexj.cloudfront.net/Midland-ER310_20180112-171256_fullsize.jpg" width="570" height="380" class="cf3feb4c c882c9ce" loading="lazy"/></div></a></div><div class="ce2bb787"><div><h3 class="b550f131 e26624a1 a1a87f29"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/12995/37027/4/167789?merchant=Amazon" class="dfb6b88d" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" title="Midland ER310" data-gtm-element="callout_product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="12995" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/12995/37027/4/167789?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_name" data-scp="callout_product" data-gtm-context="inline">Midland ER310</a></h3><h2 class="eafb159a"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/12995/37027/4/167789?merchant=Amazon" class="c44f6873" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" title="Tough, dynamic, and rechargeable" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/12995/37027/4/167789?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_title" data-scp="callout_title" data-pid="12995" data-gtm-context="inline">Tough, dynamic, and rechargeable</a></h2></div><p class="ec57f3ca" data-scp="callout_description">With great radio reception, NOAA early-warning notifications, and a hand crank that effectively revives it, the ER310 is a durable, compact radio that doubles as a flashlight and charging station.</p><div class="dded66b7"><div data-scp="removed"><h4 class="efa3259d">Buying Options</h4><div class="b279b202 product-pricebox-0" data-source-id-order="0" data-country-code="US"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/12995/37027/4/167789?merchant=Amazon" class="b50e01ee" data-gtm-element="callout_buy_button_impression" data-link-type="button" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="12995" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/12995/37027/4/167789?merchant=Amazon" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-gtm-context="inline" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_button"><span>$60</span> from <span>Amazon</span></a></div><div class="b279b202 product-pricebox-1" data-source-id-order="1" data-country-code="US"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/12995/188367/4/167789?merchant=Best%20Buy" class="b50e01ee" data-gtm-element="callout_buy_button_impression" data-link-type="button" data-merchant="Best Buy" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="12995" data-store="Best Buy" data-vars-store="Best Buy" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/12995/188367/4/167789?merchant=Best%20Buy" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-gtm-context="inline" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_button"><span>$70</span> from <span>Best Buy</span></a></div><div class="b279b202 product-pricebox-2" data-source-id-order="2" data-country-code="US"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/12995/187920/4/167789?merchant=REI" class="b50e01ee" data-gtm-element="callout_buy_button_impression" data-link-type="button" data-merchant="REI" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="12995" data-store="REI" data-vars-store="REI" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/12995/187920/4/167789?merchant=REI" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-gtm-context="inline" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_button"><span>$70</span> from <span>REI</span></a></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>A <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-emergency-weather-radio/">good emergency weather radio</a> can tune in to AM/FM and <a href="http://www.noaa.gov/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration</a> channels (collectively known as the “weather band”) to keep you informed as well as entertained if the power goes out. The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/12995/37027/4/167853/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/12995/37027/4/167853/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_communication-and-power" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="12995" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/12995/37027/4/167853/?merchant=Amazon">Midland ER310</a> offers better reception, a brighter flashlight, and more-effective charging options than other <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-emergency-weather-radio/#the-competition">radios we tested</a>, including the ability to charge from dead through solar power or hand-cranking. It can receive NOAA extreme-weather alerts, providing notifications that are both loud and readily visible so you won’t miss any warnings.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The ER310’s convenient size makes it comfortable to carry. It was also one of the few radios we tested that lived up to their crank-generating claims: We found that just one minute of cranking produced 10 minutes of radio time or a few minutes of flashlight use. Plus, its durable body can stand up to <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-emergency-weather-radio/#how-we-tested">heavy rain or a drop onto a hard surface</a>.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>If there’s an emergency alert in your area, the ER310’s built-in NOAA audible alarm and flashing display will make sure you notice. When the siren sounds and the lights begin blaring—it can be quite clamorous—you can press any button to switch the radio to your preferred (preprogrammed) NOAA weather channel to get the news.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>If you fail to turn on the radio before a minute goes by, the weather memory indicator flashes every five seconds to let you know that an alert has been issued, and it continues to do so until you press any button to turn the notice off. So if you have hearing loss, or if you’re out of the house when the alarm goes off, you can still find out if some ugly conditions are headed your way.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The flashlight also has an SOS blinking pattern, and the radio has a button that sets off a high-pitched tone—beyond the range of human hearing—to attract the attention of rescue dogs if you’re really in distress.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><h3>Power inverter (for the car)</h3></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><div class="ebb615ab global-cob eaaa9459 e1e566ad d097cc30" data-scp="callout"><h4 class="d02b79e1 e20b6350" data-scp="callout_label">Our pick</h4><div id="callout-chapter-1-18" class="fd1ac384" data-scp="callout_item" data-testid="callout" data-pid="10169"><span class="ddf294c5"><div class="fabe3ad3"><div class="e14704b2" role="button" tabindex="0" data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="10169"><span aria-label="Save Product" class="a478f5d2  " data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="10169"></span></div></div></span><div class="f1cabe17"><div class="f31f6df1"><div class="efc734d0 eae76d54"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/10169/28782/4/167791?merchant=Amazon" class="fa8c1483 product-merchant-link-button" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/lin