/span></a></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/5860/16784/4/167866/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/5860/16784/4/167866/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_tools" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="5860" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/5860/16784/4/167866/?merchant=Amazon">Leatherman Skeletool CX</a> is a multifunction tool that everyone should consider as a component of their emergency-preparedness kit, if not as a part of their everyday gear. It stood out from the <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-multitool/">other 18 multi-tools we tested</a> by focusing on the functionality and construction of a few essential tools (instead of cramming dozens of tools into a single bulky body). The tools include pliers, a bit driver, a pocket clip, and a carabiner/bottle opener. It also has a high-quality, 2.6-inch 154CM carbon-fiber stainless steel blade, which you can deploy with one hand—a great feature you won’t find on many other multi-tools.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>We also like that the carabiner adds the convenience and security of being able to attach the multi-tool to a backpack or a belt loop, rather than just having it loose in a pocket.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><h3>Gas can</h3></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><div class="ebb615ab global-cob eaaa9459 e1e566ad d097cc30" data-scp="callout"><h4 class="d02b79e1 e20b6350" data-scp="callout_label">Our pick</h4><div id="callout-chapter-1-21" class="fd1ac384" data-scp="callout_item" data-testid="callout" data-pid="11045"><span class="ddf294c5"><div class="fabe3ad3"><div class="e14704b2" role="button" tabindex="0" data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="11045"><span aria-label="Save Product" class="a478f5d2  " data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="11045"></span></div></div></span><div class="f1cabe17"><div class="f31f6df1"><div class="efc734d0 eae76d54"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11045/30996/4/167797?merchant=Amazon" class="fa8c1483 product-merchant-link-button" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11045/30996/4/167797?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_image" data-scp="removed" tabindex="-1" data-pid="11045" data-gtm-context="inline"><div class="ec5f8867 global_chapter__arp_image"><img alt="" itemProp="image" data-src="https://d1b5h9psu9yexj.cloudfront.net/11045/No-Spill-2---Gallon-Can_20201006-154303_full.jpeg" width="570" height="380" class="cf3feb4c c882c9ce" loading="lazy"/></div></a></div><div class="ce2bb787"><div><h3 class="b550f131 e26624a1 a1a87f29"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11045/30996/4/167797?merchant=Amazon" class="dfb6b88d" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" title="No-Spill 2½ Gallon Can" data-gtm-element="callout_product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="11045" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11045/30996/4/167797?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_name" data-scp="callout_product" data-gtm-context="inline">No-Spill 2½ Gallon Can</a></h3><h2 class="eafb159a"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11045/30996/4/167797?merchant=Amazon" class="c44f6873" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" title="The best gas can" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11045/30996/4/167797?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_title" data-scp="callout_title" data-pid="11045" data-gtm-context="inline">The best gas can</a></h2></div><p class="ec57f3ca" data-scp="callout_description">In our tests, this gas can had the easiest spout to operate by far, and it didn’t spill a drop when pouring.</p><div class="dded66b7"><div data-scp="removed"><h4 class="efa3259d">Buying Options</h4><div class="b279b202 product-pricebox-0" data-source-id-order="0" data-country-code="US"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11045/30996/4/167797?merchant=Amazon" class="b50e01ee" data-gtm-element="callout_buy_button_impression" data-link-type="button" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="11045" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11045/30996/4/167797?merchant=Amazon" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-gtm-context="inline" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_button"><span>$25</span> from <span>Amazon</span></a></div><div class="b279b202 product-pricebox-1" data-source-id-order="1" data-country-code="US"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11045/162004/4/167797?merchant=Home%20Depot" class="b50e01ee" data-gtm-element="callout_buy_button_impression" data-link-type="button" data-merchant="Home Depot" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="11045" data-store="Home Depot" data-vars-store="Home Depot" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11045/162004/4/167797?merchant=Home%20Depot" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-gtm-context="inline" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_button"><span>$37</span> from <span>Home Depot</span></a></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>Storing a couple of gallons of gasoline in a <a href="http://nasdonline.org/document/919/d000760/storing-gasoline-and-other-flammables.html" rel="noopener" target="_blank">safe place</a>—away from your house, not in your car, and far from electrical equipment or other potential sources of flame—is something you might consider if you’re pairing the gas with a backup generator. Gas loses potency over time, so long-term supplies need to be preserved with an <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11044/30995/4/167862/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11044/30995/4/167862/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_tools" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="11044" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11044/30995/4/167862/?merchant=Amazon">additive</a> product. But even then, you should rotate it out at least <a href="https://www.bobvila.com/articles/how-to-store-gasoline/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">once a year</a>—<a href="https://www.bobvila.com/articles/how-to-dispose-of-gasoline/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">if not every season</a>.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>Having an empty gas can around is a good idea in case you ever need to obtain or transfer gas without a car—<a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/11/business/hurricane-sandy-and-the-disaster-preparedness-economy.html?_r=0">gas cans were among the most coveted items during Hurricane Sandy</a>. Full or empty, the container you choose should be leakproof and easy to pour with.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The 2½-gallon <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11045/30996/4/167863/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11045/30996/4/167863/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_tools" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="11045" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11045/30996/4/167863/?merchant=Amazon">No-Spill</a> stands out because it has a patented, proven nozzle design that prevents spills; you just push a button and pour. We also like its unique fuel-level window, which lets you see how much gas is in the can. Note that our chosen size weighs close to 17 pounds when full. You might want to opt for No-Spill’s <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11046/30997/4/167864/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11046/30997/4/167864/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_tools" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="11046" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11046/30997/4/167864/?merchant=Amazon">1¼-gallon</a> version for easier transport if you live in, say, a flood zone and anticipate possibly needing to evacuate. A <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11047/30998/4/167865/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11047/30998/4/167865/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_tools" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="11047" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11047/30998/4/167865/?merchant=Amazon">5-gallon</a> version is also available, and both have the same great nozzle.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><h3>Gas shut-off tool</h3></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><div class="ebb615ab global-cob eaaa9459 e1e566ad d097cc30" data-scp="callout"><h4 class="d02b79e1 e20b6350" data-scp="callout_label">Our pick</h4><div id="callout-chapter-1-23" class="fd1ac384" data-scp="callout_item" data-testid="callout" data-pid="11043"><span class="ddf294c5"><div class="fabe3ad3"><div class="e14704b2" role="button" tabindex="0" data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="11043"><span aria-label="Save Product" class="a478f5d2  " data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="11043"></span></div></div></span><div class="f1cabe17"><div class="f31f6df1"><div class="efc734d0 eae76d54"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11043/30994/4/167799?merchant=Amazon" class="fa8c1483 product-merchant-link-button" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11043/30994/4/167799?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_image" data-scp="removed" tabindex="-1" data-pid="11043" data-gtm-context="inline"><div class="ec5f8867 global_chapter__arp_image"><img alt="" itemProp="image" data-src="https://d1b5h9psu9yexj.cloudfront.net/11043/SurvivalKitsOnline-On-Duty-Emergency-Gas-and-Water-Shutoff-4-in-1-Tool_20191004-180124_full.jpg" width="570" height="380" class="cf3feb4c c882c9ce" loading="lazy"/></div></a></div><div class="ce2bb787"><div><h3 class="b550f131 e26624a1 a1a87f29"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11043/30994/4/167799?merchant=Amazon" class="dfb6b88d" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" title="SurvivalKitsOnline On-Duty Emergency Gas and Water Shutoff 4-in-1 Tool" data-gtm-element="callout_product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="11043" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11043/30994/4/167799?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_name" data-scp="callout_product" data-gtm-context="inline">SurvivalKitsOnline On-Duty Emergency Gas and Water Shutoff 4-in-1 Tool</a></h3><h2 class="eafb159a"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11043/30994/4/167799?merchant=Amazon" class="c44f6873" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" title="The best gas shutoff tool" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11043/30994/4/167799?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_title" data-scp="callout_title" data-pid="11043" data-gtm-context="inline">The best gas shutoff tool</a></h2></div><p class="ec57f3ca" data-scp="callout_description">This simple but versatile wrench was invented for disaster response.</p><div class="dded66b7"><div data-scp="removed"><h4 class="efa3259d">Buying Options</h4><div class="b279b202 product-pricebox-0" data-source-id-order="0" data-country-code="US"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11043/30994/4/167799?merchant=Amazon" class="b50e01ee" data-gtm-element="callout_buy_button_impression" data-link-type="button" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="11043" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11043/30994/4/167799?merchant=Amazon" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-gtm-context="inline" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_button"><span>$20</span> from <span>Amazon</span></a></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>If you smell, hear, or see evidence of a gas leak in the aftermath of a disaster, your first priority is to <a href="http://www.pge.com/en/safety/gaselectricsafety/turngasoff/index.page" rel="noopener" target="_blank">turn your gas off</a>. To accomplish that, you need to do two simple things: Learn where your gas valve is (ahead of time), and find a wrench that will do the job.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>A quarter-turn of the metal gas valve from the vertical to the horizontal position typically shuts off your supply. In almost all cases, a 12-inch or larger adjustable wrench will work. If you already have one, consider keeping it in a waterproof Ziploc bag duct-taped to a wall or pipe next to the valve. That’ll ensure you won’t have to spend even a minute looking for it in an emergency.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>Alternatively, you can purchase a dedicated shutoff tool. After a couple of hours of online research and discussions with a handful of experts, we feel comfortable recommending the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11043/30994/4/167867/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11043/30994/4/167867/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_tools" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="11043" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/11043/30994/4/167867/?merchant=Amazon">On-Duty Emergency Gas and Water Shutoff 4-in-1 Tool</a>. It was <a href="http://www.onduty1.com/aboutus.html" rel="noopener" target="_blank">designed by firefighters</a> in the aftermath of the San Francisco Bay Area’s 1989 Loma Prieta earthquake and is often recommended to students of <a href="http://www.fema.gov/community-emergency-response-teams" rel="noopener" target="_blank">CERT emergency-preparedness classes</a>.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The 11-inch aluminum tool is sturdy and rustproof, and it won’t risk causing a spark, as a steel tool hitting steel might (an important consideration when gas is leaking). You can also use it to shut off your water valve, pry open doors, and dig through debris.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>Don’t be too quick to use it, though. Smell a leak? Yes, turn off the gas. But note that in many cities, the gas company may have to <a href="https://www.nyc.gov/site/buildings/tenant/gas-cut-off.page" rel="noopener" target="_blank">come to your home</a> to turn your gas back on. In a citywide disaster, scheduling that visit could take days or even weeks. So avoid turning the gas off preemptively if you’ll need it to cook, boil water, or heat your home during a blackout or some other power outage.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><h3>Signaling whistle</h3></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><div class="ebb615ab global-cob eaaa9459 e1e566ad d097cc30" data-scp="callout"><h4 class="d02b79e1 e20b6350" data-scp="callout_label">Our pick</h4><div id="callout-chapter-1-24" class="fd1ac384" data-scp="callout_item" data-testid="callout" data-pid="10189"><span class="ddf294c5"><div class="fabe3ad3"><div class="e14704b2" role="button" tabindex="0" data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="10189"><span aria-label="Save Product" class="a478f5d2  " data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="10189"></span></div></div></span><div class="f1cabe17"><div class="f31f6df1"><div class="efc734d0 eae76d54"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/10189/28831/4/167800?merchant=Amazon" class="fa8c1483 product-merchant-link-button" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/10189/28831/4/167800?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_image" data-scp="removed" tabindex="-1" data-pid="10189" data-gtm-context="inline"><div class="ec5f8867 global_chapter__arp_image"><img alt="" itemProp="image" data-src="https://d1b5h9psu9yexj.cloudfront.net/10189/Shoreline-Marine-Emergency-Survival-Whistle_20181018-161508_full.jpeg" width="570" height="380" class="cf3feb4c c882c9ce" loading="lazy"/></div></a></div><div class="ce2bb787"><div><h3 class="b550f131 e26624a1 a1a87f29"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/10189/28831/4/167800?merchant=Amazon" class="dfb6b88d" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" title="Shoreline Marine Emergency Survival Whistle" data-gtm-element="callout_product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="10189" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/10189/28831/4/167800?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_name" data-scp="callout_product" data-gtm-context="inline">Shoreline Marine Emergency Survival Whistle</a></h3><h2 class="eafb159a"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/10189/28831/4/167800?merchant=Amazon" class="c44f6873" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" title="The best signaling whistle" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/10189/28831/4/167800?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_title" data-scp="callout_title" data-pid="10189" data-gtm-context="inline">The best signaling whistle</a></h2></div><p class="ec57f3ca" data-scp="callout_description">This cheap, brightly colored whistle proved louder and easier to hear at a distance than more expensive products.</p><div class="dded66b7"><div data-scp="removed"><h4 class="efa3259d">Buying Options</h4><div class="b279b202 product-pricebox-0" data-source-id-order="0" data-country-code="US"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/10189/28831/4/167800?merchant=Amazon" class="b50e01ee" data-gtm-element="callout_buy_button_impression" data-link-type="button" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="10189" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/10189/28831/4/167800?merchant=Amazon" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-gtm-context="inline" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_button"><span>$5</span> from <span>Amazon</span></a></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>No one wants to think about being trapped during a natural disaster, but it does happen. Screaming for help might get a rescuer’s attention, but the high-pitch shrill of a whistle is far more likely to cut through the din of a wildfire, windstorm, or emergency sirens.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>We tested six whistles over water in varying wind conditions and through densely wooded forest. Our conclusion: The <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/10189/28831/4/167868/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/10189/28831/4/167868/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_tools" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="10189" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/10189/28831/4/167868/?merchant=Amazon">Shoreline Marine Emergency Survival Whistle</a> is the best choice for disaster preparedness. It was both the loudest and cheapest model, registering a piercing 101.1 decibels, according to <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/8139/23719/4/167869/?merchant=Apple%20App%20Store" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Apple App Store" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/8139/23719/4/167869/?merchant=Apple%20App%20Store" data-vars-store="Apple App Store" data-gtm-context="chapter_tools" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Apple App Store" data-pid="8139" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/8139/23719/4/167869/?merchant=Apple%20App%20Store">NoiSee</a> (a sound-measurement app we used that ranks highly with the <a href="http://blogs.cdc.gov/niosh-science-blog/2014/04/09/sound-apps/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health</a>). The only whistle that registered more loudly, the Acme Thunderer metal coach’s whistle (101.2 decibels), wasn’t audible at longer distances.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 d50e62cc dc955d9e b9a20fb4 d1e713dc"><aside class="f46340a9"><p data-scp="pullquote">If you ever need to use one, call on the international whistle code: One blast means “Where are you?” Two blasts mean “Come to me.” Three blasts mean “I need help.”</p></aside></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>The Shoreline is brightly colored (and thus easy to spot), and because it looks like a normal whistle, almost anyone can pick it up and instinctively know how to use it. In an emergency, the whistle is even more useful if you memorize the international whistle code: One blast means “Where are you?” Two blasts mean “Come to me.” Three blasts mean “I need help.” (Each blast should last three seconds.)</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><h3>Duct tape</h3></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><div class="ebb615ab global-cob eaaa9459 e1e566ad d097cc30" data-scp="callout"><h4 class="d02b79e1 e20b6350" data-scp="callout_label">Our pick</h4><div id="callout-chapter-1-25" class="fd1ac384" data-scp="callout_item" data-testid="callout" data-pid="330"><span class="ddf294c5"><div class="fabe3ad3"><div class="e14704b2" role="button" tabindex="0" data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="330"><span aria-label="Save Product" class="a478f5d2  " data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="330"></span></div></div></span><div class="f1cabe17"><div class="f31f6df1"><div class="efc734d0 eae76d54"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/330/201063/4/167801?merchant=Amazon" class="fa8c1483 product-merchant-link-button" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/330/201063/4/167801?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_image" data-scp="removed" tabindex="-1" data-pid="330" data-gtm-context="inline"><div class="ec5f8867 global_chapter__arp_image"><img alt="" itemProp="image" data-src="https://d1b5h9psu9yexj.cloudfront.net/330/Duck-Max-Strength_20190624-160244_full.jpg" width="570" height="380" class="cf3feb4c c882c9ce" loading="lazy"/></div></a></div><div class="ce2bb787"><div><h3 class="b550f131 e26624a1 a1a87f29"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wire