="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/16130/197180/4/167804?merchant=Lowe&#x27;s" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-gtm-context="inline" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_button"><span>$60</span> from <span>Lowe&#x27;s</span></a></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>Aside from being as effective against all types of common household fires (wood and paper, burning liquids, electrical) as other models like it, the <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/16130/48250/4/167860/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/16130/48250/4/167860/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_tools" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="16130" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/16130/48250/4/167860/?merchant=Amazon">First Alert PRO5</a> has further advantages. First, it exceeds the minimum size recommendations of the <a href="https://www.nfpa.org/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">National Fire Protection Association</a> (NFPA) yet weighs a manageable 5 pounds.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>We also prefer this type over a disposable model because it has a sturdy and reliable metal valve (not plastic). And if you have to use the PRO5, you can refill it for about half the cost of getting a new extinguisher. You can find <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-fire-extinguisher/">a number of extinguishers</a> that share most of the PRO5’s features, but we found that the PRO5 has the edge because of its wide availability. This is one pick you’ll definitely want to keep somewhere handy, like the kitchen, instead of stashed away in an emergency kit.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><h3>Cleanup gloves</h3></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><div class="ebb615ab global-cob eaaa9459 e1e566ad d097cc30" data-scp="callout"><h4 class="d02b79e1 e20b6350" data-scp="callout_label">Our pick</h4><div id="callout-chapter-1-29" class="fd1ac384" data-scp="callout_item" data-testid="callout" data-pid="29009"><span class="ddf294c5"><div class="fabe3ad3"><div class="e14704b2" role="button" tabindex="0" data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="29009"><span aria-label="Save Product" class="a478f5d2  " data-gtm-trigger="save_product" data-save-content-value="true" data-save-content-id="29009"></span></div></div></span><div class="f1cabe17"><div class="f31f6df1"><div class="efc734d0 eae76d54"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/29009/148807/4/167805?merchant=Amazon" class="fa8c1483 product-merchant-link-button" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/29009/148807/4/167805?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_image" data-scp="removed" tabindex="-1" data-pid="29009" data-gtm-context="inline"><div class="ec5f8867 global_chapter__arp_image"><img alt="" itemProp="image" data-src="https://d1b5h9psu9yexj.cloudfront.net/29009/Custom-Leathercraft-124L-Flex-Grip-WorkRight-Gloves_20181018-161323_full.jpeg" width="570" height="380" class="cf3feb4c c882c9ce" loading="lazy"/></div></a></div><div class="ce2bb787"><div><h3 class="b550f131 e26624a1 a1a87f29"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/29009/148807/4/167805?merchant=Amazon" class="dfb6b88d" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" title="Custom Leathercraft 124 Flex Grip WorkRight Gloves" data-gtm-element="callout_product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="29009" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/29009/148807/4/167805?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_name" data-scp="callout_product" data-gtm-context="inline">Custom Leathercraft 124 Flex Grip WorkRight Gloves</a></h3><h2 class="eafb159a"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/29009/148807/4/167805?merchant=Amazon" class="c44f6873" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" title="The best gloves for emergency use" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/29009/148807/4/167805?merchant=Amazon" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_title" data-scp="callout_title" data-pid="29009" data-gtm-context="inline">The best gloves for emergency use</a></h2></div><p class="ec57f3ca" data-scp="callout_description">Protect your hands with these inexpensive and lightweight gloves. Unlike most leather work gloves, they offer great dexterity.</p><div class="dded66b7"><div data-scp="removed"><h4 class="efa3259d">Buying Options</h4><div class="b279b202 product-pricebox-0" data-source-id-order="0" data-country-code="US"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/29009/148807/4/167805?merchant=Amazon" class="b50e01ee" data-gtm-element="callout_buy_button_impression" data-link-type="button" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="29009" data-store="Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/29009/148807/4/167805?merchant=Amazon" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-gtm-context="inline" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_button"><span>$15</span> from <span>Amazon</span></a></div><div class="b279b202 product-pricebox-1" data-source-id-order="1" data-country-code="US"><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/29009/152672/4/167805?merchant=Walmart" class="b50e01ee" data-gtm-element="callout_buy_button_impression" data-link-type="button" data-merchant="Walmart" data-pick-type-id="1" data-pid="29009" data-store="Walmart" data-vars-store="Walmart" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/29009/152672/4/167805?merchant=Walmart" rel="sponsored noreferrer" target="_blank" data-gtm-context="inline" data-gtm-trigger="callout_product_link_button"><span>$23</span> from <span>Walmart</span></a></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>In an emergency situation, your hands can be exposed to a lot of hazards, whether you’re cleaning up broken glass or pulling branches from your driveway. For protection, we recommend getting a pair of <a class="product-link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/29009/148807/4/167859/?merchant=Amazon" rel="noopener sponsored" target="_blank" data-gtm-trigger="product_link" data-store="Amazon" data-pick-type-id="1" data-vars-outbound-link="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/29009/148807/4/167859/?merchant=Amazon" data-vars-store="Amazon" data-gtm-context="chapter_tools" data-gtm-element="product_link_impression" data-link-type="link" data-merchant="Amazon" data-pid="29009" data-url="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/out/link/29009/148807/4/167859/?merchant=Amazon">Custom Leathercraft 124L Flex Grip WorkRight Gloves</a>. They’re comfortable and inexpensive, and compared with the regular, floppy leather work gloves <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-gear-for-your-bug-out-bag/#protective-gear">we tested</a>, they offer great dexterity. There’s no need to take them off for more delicate tasks such as reaching into a pocket, tying a shoelace, or starting a car.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>They’re not especially high-quality, so if you use them on a daily basis, they’ll likely wear out in a month or two. But as a pair of gloves to keep in an emergency kit, they are a great value. Although these gloves are available only in medium, large, and extra-large, buyer comments on retail sites indicate the medium size works fine for smaller hands.</p></div></div></div></div></div></section><section class="b6d81848 d47f7b03" id="storage" expanded=""><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0 e5f9b502"><h2 class="e823fba7" aria-controls="storage-panel" aria-selected="true" role="tab" tabindex="0" data-gtm-element="chapter_heading" data-gtm-trigger="single_chapter" data-chapter-name="Storage" data-expand-close="close" data-chapter-index="8">Storage</h2></div></div><div id="storage-panel" class="fa265be5" aria-labelledby="storage" aria-hidden="false" role="tabpanel"><div class=" chapter__content-wrapper"><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>Your supplies need to be <a href="https://www.nyc.gov/site/em/ready/get-prepared.page" rel="noopener" target="_blank">easily accessible</a>, but where exactly you store your cache of disaster supplies will depend on your region and your risk factors. Is flooding a probable hazard? Don’t keep your emergency gear in the basement.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><p>For those in earthquake territory, storing supplies outside may make the most sense, especially if you live in a mild climate and don’t have to worry about freezing temperatures that can damage your items. In the 1994 Northridge earthquake in California, garage doors were knocked off-kilter and jammed, trapping supplies inside. If you’re storing your gear outside in a warm climate, choose a cool, shaded spot, to avoid sun damage.</p></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b5823c44 cdde21c0"><h3>Storage container</h3></div></div></div><div><div class="a1497183"><div class="f21e64f1 b