ps://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-all-purpose-cleaner/"},"children":[{"data":"disinfectants","type":"text"}]},{"data":" and ","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"a","attribs":{"class":"product-link","href":"https://wclink.co/link/40973/165771/4/167834/?merchant=Amazon","rel":"noopener sponsored","target":"_blank","data-gtm-trigger":"product_link","data-store":"Amazon"},"children":[{"data":"nitrile gloves","type":"text"}]},{"data":" around.","type":"text"}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"p","attribs":{},"children":[{"type":"tag","name":"em","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"This article was edited by Joshua Lyon and Harry Sawyers.","type":"text"}]}]},{"data":"\n","type":"text"}],"bodyContent":"As mentioned, we have dedicated preparedness guides for disasters like hurricanes, earthquakes, snow storms, and wildfires, but they’re not the only types of disaster one might experience. Tornados Tornado alley is moving eastward, and it’s important for everyone to be aware of how to react in this type of weather event even if your area hasn’t been affected in the past. A NOAA-equipped weather radio will help you keep track of a tornado watch alert, which means there’s a potential for tornados, and a tornado warning alert, which means one or more has been sighted or indicated by weather radar. Identify the best safe room in your home (a storm cellar, a basement, or an interior room on the lowest floor, preferably with no windows) and gather there before the storm hits (bring your pets, too!). FEMA has recommendations for where to go, depending on where you are when a storm is approaching. Flying debris is a major tornado hazard. If your safe room contains windows or unattached objects, covering yourself with a heavy blanket could help. When you emerge, wear sturdy shoes and heavy gloves to protect yourself from broken glass. The CDC recommends using a helmet if you have quick access to one; but the agency also says that spending time looking for a helmet could delay the more-crucial goal of getting to a safe space. Scientists at the University of Alabama at Birmingham say they can be lifesavers (especially motorcycle helmets with a full-face shield). Tsunamis Are you in a tsunami risk zone such as the Pacific Northwest coast? Did you just feel a big earthquake? Do not pause to grab anything. Just move to high ground. (Oregon and Washington coast dwellers, enter your address here to assess your risk.) If you aren’t familiar with the quickest route to higher ground from your home and work, learn it. Volcanos There are about 170 places in the United States where volcanic eruptions are possible. “A good case and example was the 1980 eruption of Mount St. Helens in Washington State that caused several [57] deaths,” says CDC press officer Scott Pauley. “More recently, a 2018 Kīlauea eruption in Hawaii destroyed hundreds of homes, buried subdivisions and affected air quality.” Much of the preparation advice for volcanoes is similar to the other disasters that may require you to either evacuate or shelter in place: wildfires or hurricanes. A special consideration is that you will want extra respiratory and eye protection in your emergency kit if you live in an area where volcanic activity is possible, like you would in an area with wildfires. Breathing in volcanic ash can harm your lungs, especially if you have a pre-existing respiratory condition like asthma. An emergency radio is crucial, since you need to follow official advice on your next moves. Be prepared to evacuate with a go bag. Radiation exposure If you learn about an imminent nuclear explosion, get inside as quickly as possible. After the blast, you have about 10 minutes to find a secure location—ideally a basement of a building with brick or concrete walls—before the fallout of sandlike radioactive particles begins. Once you are in a safe location, stay there for at least 24 hours and wait for instructions from emergency officials. Pandemics The COVID-19 pandemic required new levels of preparedness and vigilance. We’re now wiser about how to deal with a deadly, widespread coronavirus outbreak, but another pandemic is likely during the lifetimes of most people today. Many of the supplies that were useful during the COVID-19 pandemic, like masks, soap, and hand sanitizer that contains at least 60 percent alcohol, would likely continue to be effective no matter the offending microbe. The COVID-19 virus infected people mainly through the air instead of contaminated surfaces. That might not be true for future pathogens, so some states recommend keeping a supply of disinfectants and nitrile gloves around. This article was edited by Joshua Lyon and Harry Sawyers.","title":"Disaster-specific considerations","slug":"disaster-specific-considerations","chapterModifiedDate":null,"chapterPublishedDate":null,"faqs":null,"footnotes":null,"sources":null},{"body":null,"bodyContent":null,"title":"Sources","slug":"sources","chapterModifiedDate":null,"chapterPublishedDate":null,"faqs":null,"footnotes":null,"sources":[{"dateLocalDisplay":"July 26, 2023","author":"Stephanie Fox","title":"national emergency relations lead","publication":"Red Cross","url":"https://www.linkedin.com/in/stephanieyfox/","text":""},{"dateLocalDisplay":null,"author":"Jeremy Edwards","title":"press secretary","publication":"FEMA, email interview, June and July 2023","url":"https://www.linkedin.com/in/jeremy-edwards-07b682151/","text":""},{"dateLocalDisplay":"July 10, 2020","author":"Jonathan McNamara","title":"regional communications director","publication":"American Red Cross, phone interview","url":"https://www.redcross.org/","text":""},{"dateLocalDisplay":"July 3, 2023","author":"Wesley Wehde","title":"assistant professor","publication":"department of political science at Texas Tech University, Zoom interview","url":"https://www.depts.ttu.edu/politicalscience/Faculty/WehdeWesley.php","text":""},{"dateLocalDisplay":"June 26, 2023","author":"Scott Pauley","title":"press officer","publication":"CDC, email interview","url":"https://www.linkedin.com/in/scott-pauley-mps-40567058/","text":""},{"dateLocalDisplay":"January 24, 2023","author":"Olivia Asuncion","title":"project architect","publication":"Quattrocchi Kwok Architects, Zoom interview","url":"https://www.linkedin.com/in/oliviamaeasuncion/","text":""},{"dateLocalDisplay":"January 11, 2023","author":"Junghwa Choi","title":"assistant professor","publication":"School of Public Administration at the University of Nebraska at Omaha, Zoom interview","url":"https://www.unomaha.edu/college-of-public-affairs-and-community-service/public-administration/about-us/faculty-staff/junghwa-choi.php","text":""}]}],"note":{"body":"[{\"type\":\"tag\",\"name\":\"p\",\"attribs\":{},\"children\":[{\"data\":\"We’ve updated this guide with several new picks, including the \",\"type\":\"text\"},{\"type\":\"tag\",\"name\":\"a\",\"attribs\":{\"class\":\"product-link\",\"href\":\"https://wclink.co/link/54940/192466/4/167818/?merchant=Amazon\",\"rel\":\"noopener sponsored\",\"target\":\"_blank\",\"data-gtm-trigger\":\"product_link\",\"data-store\":\"Amazon\",\"data-pick-type-id\":1},\"children\":[{\"data\":\"LifeStraw Max\",\"type\":\"text\"}]},{\"data\":\" water filter and \",\"type\":\"text\"},{\"type\":\"tag\",\"name\":\"a\",\"attribs\":{\"class\":\"product-link\",\"href\":\"https://wclink.co/link/38478/162606/4/167856/?merchant=Amazon\",\"rel\":\"noopener sponsored\",\"target\":\"_blank\",\"data-gtm-trigger\":\"product_link\",\"data-store\":\"Amazon\",\"data-pick-type-id\":1},\"children\":[{\"data\":\"Jackery Explorer 1000\",\"type\":\"text\"}]},{\"data\":\" portable power station, and added a section on accessibility considerations.\",\"type\":\"text\"}]},{\"data\":\"\\n\",\"type\":\"text\"}]","date":"2023-08-30","hide":0,"label":"","summary":null,"type":"regular"},"toc":{"enabled":true,"title":null,"mobileExpanded":true},"reviewFAQ":{"expand":null,"faq":[]},"highlights":null,"primarySection